[1]The CANT Z. 1007 Alcione was a medium bomber three-engined low-wing developed by the aeronautics division of the Italian company, Cantieri Riuniti dell Adriatico in the thirties and product, as well as, also on license from other national companies.Designed by ingegner Filippo Zappata, the chief designer of the company and the author of numerous aircraft such as the CANT Z. 506 .
[3]and is considered by many authors as the "best bomber in the Italian of the second world war," although its wooden structure could be easily damaged by extreme climatic conditions, such as those encountered in north Africa and in the Soviet Union.
[2]it was characterized by the wooden structure, "excellent flying qualities and good stability" .
[4]During the conflict was mainly used by the Regia Aeronautica, the Italian air force of the period, and then, after the events following the signing of the armistice of Cassibile by the air force Cobelligerante Italian, air force, National Republican, and the Luftwaffe.
